    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT176-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">tōḻi kiḻattiyaik kuṟainayappak kūṟiyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Spoken by the confidante, that SHE would yield to [his] request.</p>
          </div>


        <div xml:id="KT176">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                orunāḷ vārala ṉirunāḷ vāralaṉ</l>
<l>                paṉṉāḷ vantu paṇimoḻi payiṟṟiyeṉ</l>
<l>                ṉaṉṉar neñca nekiḻtta piṉṟai</l>
<l>                varaimutir tēṉiṟ pōki yōṉē</l>
<l>                yācā kentai yāṇṭuḷaṉ kollō</l>
<l>                vēṟupula ṉaṉṉāṭṭup peyta</l>
<l>                vēṟuṭai maḻaiyiṟ kaluḻumeṉ ṉeñcē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
           <l>For one day he didn't come, for two days he didn't come,</l>
           <l rend="indent">after he had come for many days, repeating humble words,</l>
           <l rend="indent">[and] made my good heart soft –</l>
           <l rend="indent">like honey ripening on the mountain,<note place="foot">This comparison would be easier to understand in connection with the softened heart, but position seems to forbid this. As it stands, the only point can be that he has disappeared like the honey will disappear as soon as it is ripe, because it will be taken away by someone.</note> he is gone.</l>
           <l>My father who is<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">āku</term> is predicative here: "the father who actually, according to definition is a prop". Or Srin.: "my father, who could become a prop [now], where is he?"</note> a prop to [me], where is he?</l>
           <l rend="indent">Like thundering rain<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ēṟu uṭai maḻai</term>: <term xml:lang="ta">ēṟu uṭai</term> can either be connected with the sound of the rain itself, that is, something like thundering rain, or what is meant is that rain comes along with thunder, that is, a thunderstorm.</note> rained on good land</l>
           <l rend="indent">with different fields<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vēṟu pulam</term>: what is meant here? Different kinds of earth, as a qualification to <term xml:lang="ta">naṉṉāṭṭu</term> (good through variety)? TVG reads something different (in accordance with Cām.), but this also does not seem very clear (and not corresponding to the usual meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">peyta</term>): "like thundering rain that had flown from other fields onto [this] good land".</note></l>
           <l rend="indent3">my heart weeps.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
